{"cursor":"10533","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox writer  |name = Euhemerus (Îá½Î®Î¼ÎµÏÎ¿Ï)\n|image = |caption = |pseudonym = |birth_date = 4th century B.C. |birth_place =\nMessene (now Messina), Sicily |death_date = 3rd century B.C. |death_place =\n|occupation = Writer, philosopher, mythographer, historian |nationality =\nAncient Greek |influences = Plato, Sophists, Cyrenaics |influenced = Ennius,\nDiodorus Siculus, Cicero, Varro, Sextus Empiricus, Philo of Byblos, Church\nFathers (e.g. Clement of Alexandria, Minucius Felix, Cyprian, Arnobius,\nLactantius, Eusebius of Caesarea, Augustine), Saxo Grammaticus, Snorri\nSturluson, Enlightenment |signature = |website =}}\n\n'Euhemerus', also spelled Euemeros, or Evemerus ( [EuhÄmeros], \"happy;\nprosperous\") (late 4th century BC) was a Greek mythographer at the court of\nCassander, the king of Macedon. Euhemerus' birthplace is disputed, with Messina\nin Sicily as the most probable location, while others champion Chios or Tegea.\n\nThe term is derived from his name, and is the philosophy attributed to Euhemerus\nwhich holds that many mythological tales can be attributed to historical persons\nand events, the accounts of which have become altered and exaggerated over time.\n\nEuhemerusâs work combined elements of fiction and political utopianism. In the\nancient world he was considered an atheist. Early Christian writers, such as\nLactantius, used Euhemerus's belief that the ancient gods were originally human\nto confirm their inferiority regarding the Christian god.\n","linknr":251,"url":"Euhemerus","recorded":1374548571,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Euhemerus&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Euhemerus&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en